.Sh NOTES
Although the module header describes
.Fn graph_dfs_al
and its type-specific variants as an
.Dq iterative-recursive
DFS, the current implementation
.Pq i_dfs_visit_recursive
recurses directly on the call stack, with recursion depth bounded by
the longest path in the graph. On stack-constrained embedded targets,
a sufficiently deep or pathological
.Pq e.g. near-linear-chain
graph can exhaust the stack. Callers targeting such platforms should
bound input graph depth accordingly, or convert the traversal to an
explicit-stack iterative form.
.Pp
.Fn graph_bfs_al
and
.Fn dgraph_bfs_al
are defined only for the unweighted graph types
.Pq Vt graph_t No and Vt dgraph_t ;
none of the weighted CSR types
.Pq Vt wigraph_t , wfgraph_t , widgraph_t , wfdgraph_t
have a BFS entry point, since shortest paths on weighted graphs are
served by
.Fn wigraph_dijkstra_al
and its variants instead.
.Pp
The Dijkstra family
.Pq Fn wigraph_dijkstra_al , Fn widgraph_dijkstra_al , Fn wfgraph_dijkstra_al , Fn wfdgraph_dijkstra_al
requires all edge weights to be non-negative; a negative weight
produces undefined shortest-path results without diagnostic. Graphs
with negative weights should instead use the Floyd-Warshall family,
which detects negative cycles via
.Va has_negative_cycle .
.Pp
The Floyd-Warshall family runs in
.Sy O(V^3)
time and
.Sy O(V^2)
space
.Pq two Va n Ns * Ns Va n No matrices ,
which can become a substantial memory cost for large vertex counts
even when the underlying CSR storage is sparse.
.Pp
.Fn wigraph_kruskal_al
and
.Fn wfgraph_kruskal_al
are defined only for the undirected weighted types
.Pq Vt wigraph_t No and Vt wfgraph_t ;
there is no directed-graph MST variant, as minimum spanning trees are
defined over undirected graphs.
.Pp
Functions suffixed
.Sy _al
allocate and transfer ownership of every pointer in their result to
the caller
.Pq see Sx Memory ownership No in Sx DESCRIPTION ;
mixing these results with the module's
.Fn *_destroy
functions, or vice versa, is undefined behavior.
.Sh EXAMPLES
The following programs demonstrate the use of all the functions listed above.
They serve as test cases for every feature provided by the header.
.Bl -tag -width -5n -offset -6n
.It Sy Depth-first search program
.El
.Bl -tag -width 0
.El
.Bd -literal
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

#define GRAPH_IMPLEMENTATION
#include "graph.h"

void graphtest_undirected(void)
{
	/* Example graph (0-indexed, undirected):
	 *   0 -- 1
	 *   2 -- 3
	 *   3 -- 0
	 * vertex_count = 4, edge_count = 3
	 */
	edge_t edges[] = {
		{0, 1},
		{2, 3},
		{3, 0},
	};
	graph_size_t edge_count   = 3;
	graph_size_t vertex_count = 4;
	graph_t g;
	graph_dfs_result_t result;
	graph_size_t i;

	graph_construct(&g, edges, vertex_count, edge_count);
	result = graph_dfs_al(&g);

	printf("[graph_t] component_count: %u\n", result.component_count);
	printf("[graph_t] has_cycle: %s\n", result.has_cycle ? "yes" : "no");
	printf("[graph_t] component_id: ");
	for (i = 0; i < vertex_count; i++) printf("%u ", result.component_id[i]);
	printf("\n[graph_t] postorder: ");
	for (i = 0; i < vertex_count; i++) printf("%u ", result.postorder[i]);
	printf("\n");

	free(result.component_id);
	free(result.postorder);
	graph_destroy(&g);
}

void graphtest_directed(void)
{
	/* Same shape, directed:
	 *   0 -> 1
	 *   2 -> 3
	 *   3 -> 0
	 */
	edge_t edges[] = {
		{0, 1},
		{2, 3},
		{3, 0},
	};
	graph_size_t edge_count   = 3;
	graph_size_t vertex_count = 4;
